ENTRY            C3097   20251212   20260312   20260312       C253
SUBENT        C3097001   20251212   20260312   20260312       C253
BIB                 13         44
TITLE      Probing the most important 14O(alpha,p)17F
           resonance through a study of 17F(p,p')17F*
AUTHOR     (S.Coil,D.W.Bardayan,P.D.O'Malley,T.L.Bailey,
           C.Boomershine,S.Carmichael,C.Dembski,T.Gore,A.M.Houff,
           C.Jones,J.J.Kolata,K.Lee,G.Mulcahy,W.S.Porter,
           F.Rivero,J.Rufino,A.Sanchez,W.W.Von Seeger,L.Zimmer,
           R.Zite)
INSTITUTE  (1USANOT,1USAMSU)
REFERENCE  (J,PR/C,112,035804,2025)
           #doi:10.1103/bljj-k2nv
FACILITY   (ACCEL,1USANOT) The University of Notre Dame Nuclear
           Science Laboratory TriSol radioactive beam facility.
INC-SOURCE A 17F beam was produced using primary beams of 16O at
           five discrete beam energies between 58 and 67 MeV to
           bombard a deuterium-filled (~800 Torr) gas cell with
           4-microm Ti windows.
INC-SPECT  (EN-SEC) Typical full width at half maximum (FWHM)
           energy and angular spreads were 800 keV and 0.8.,
           respectively. Typical 17F beam intensities were
           approximately 10**4 pps, which was limited by the
           counting rates in the ionization chamber. In addition
           to 17F, the beam also contained 16O at a ratio of
           16O/17F ~ 40/60. This ratio varied slightly between
           beam energy changes but was stable once a tune was
           established for a given energy.
PART-DET   (P)
DETECTOR   (SISD,TELES,IOCH) An array of Micron YY1-style
           silicon- strip detectors. Two telescopes consisting
           of a 73-microm-thick detector backed by a
           498-microm-thick detector were implemented. Pressures
           ranging from 30 to 48 Torr of P10 gas were used
           within the ionization chamber.
SAMPLE     4-microm-thick CH2 target (376 microg/cm2).
METHOD     (EDE) The optimized 17F beam was then impinged onto
           CH2 target. Protons scattered from the target were
           detected with an array of silicon-strip detectors
           covering an angular range from 8.7 to 20.4 degrees in
           the laboratory frame. Recoils were counted in the
           downstream ionization chamber. The data acquisition
           was set to trigger only by events in the silicon
           detectors to avoid excessive dead time from the high
           counting rates of the ionization chamber.
STATUS     (APRVD) Approved by D.W.Bardayan on December 17, 2025.
HISTORY    (20251212C) BP
